#compdef easy-add
# ============================================================================
# easy-add - download a release archive (tar.gz/
#             tgz/zip) + extract a single file
#             from within it (Go, MIT)
#
# Author : Geoff Bourne (itzg)
# Upstream: https://github.com/itzg/easy-add
#
# `easy-add` is a single-binary Go utility designed
# to simplify the `Dockerfile` pattern of:
#   1. wget/curl a GitHub release archive
#   2. tar/unzip it
#   3. mv the binary to /usr/local/bin
#   4. chmod +x it
#   5. rm the downloaded archive
# into a single command. The tool downloads a URL,
# auto-detects the archive format (.tar.gz / .tgz /
# .zip from the URL suffix), extracts a specified
# file from within the archive, and places it at
# the destination path with executable permissions
# applied.
#
# easy-add is the foundational bootstrap utility
# behind itzg/docker-minecraft-server (one of the
# most-pulled Docker images globally with ~10M+
# monthly pulls): every itzg/* image uses easy-add
# in its Dockerfile to install Minecraft server
# binaries, mod loaders, Java versions, and other
# release artifacts from GitHub at image build
# time.
#
# Use cases:
#   - Dockerfile `RUN easy-add --from <url>
#     --file <archive-path>` patterns to install
#     release artifacts in container images
#   - CI/CD pipelines that need to bootstrap tools
#     from GitHub releases
#   - Embedded Linux image build systems
#   - Self-contained installation scripts that
#     avoid the wget/tar/unzip/chmod boilerplate
#
# Usage:
#   easy-add --from <url> --file <path> \
#            [--to <dir>] [--mkdirs] \
#            [--var <key=value>]...
#
# Flags (itzg/go-flagsfiller struct-to-flag
# library; standard Go single-dash style with
# `--`-prefixed long flag aliases):
#   --from <url>                 - URL of a
#                                   tar.gz or zip
#                                   archive to
#                                   download (may
#                                   contain Go
#                                   template
#                                   references
#                                   to `--var`
#                                   entries; the
#                                   format suffix
#                                   determines
#                                   the archive
#                                   type)
#   --file <path>                - path to the
#                                   executable to
#                                   extract from
#                                   within the
#                                   archive (may
#                                   contain Go
#                                   template
#                                   references
#                                   to `--var`
#                                   entries)
#   --to <dir>                   - destination
#                                   directory for
#                                   the extracted
#                                   executable
#                                   (default
#                                   `/usr/local/
#                                   bin`)
#   --mkdirs                     - attempt to
#                                   create the
#                                   `--to`
#                                   directory if
#                                   it doesn't
#                                   exist
#   --var <key=value>            - sets variables
#                                   that can be
#                                   referenced in
#                                   `--from` and
#                                   `--file` via
#                                   Go template
#                                   substitution
#                                   (repeatable)
#   --version                    - show version
#                                   + exit
#
# Environment variables (auto-mapped by
# go-flagsfiller from struct field names):
#   EASY_ADD_FROM                - default
#                                   `--from`
#                                   value
#   EASY_ADD_FILE                - default
#                                   `--file`
#                                   value
#   EASY_ADD_TO                  - default
#                                   `--to`
#                                   value
#   EASY_ADD_MKDIRS              - default
#                                   `--mkdirs`
#                                   value
#
# Archive format detection (from URL suffix at
# main.go::getArchiveType line 225+):
#   .tar.gz / .tgz               - extracts via
#                                   archive/tar +
#                                   compress/
#                                   gzip
#   .zip                         - extracts via
#                                   archive/zip
#                                   (THIS AXIS)
#
# Example Dockerfile usage:
#   RUN curl -fsSL -o /tmp/easy-add \
#       https://github.com/itzg/easy-add/releases/download/v0.7.0/easy-add_linux_amd64 && \
#       chmod +x /tmp/easy-add && \
#       /tmp/easy-add \
#         --var version=v0.4.0 \
#         --var os=linux --var arch=amd64 \
#         --from "https://github.com/itzg/mc-image-helper/releases/download/{{.version}}/mc-image-helper-{{.version}}.zip" \
#         --file "mc-image-helper-{{.version}}/bin/mc-image-helper" \
#         --to /usr/local/bin && \
#       rm /tmp/easy-add
#
# This Dockerfile pattern is the foundational
# bootstrap step in itzg/docker-minecraft-server's
# build process - the world's most-pulled
# Minecraft-server Docker image.
#
# The archive/zip lane is built on Go's stdlib
# `archive/zip` package (imported as
# `"archive/zip"` in main.go line 5, used at
# line 163 as `zipReader, err :=
# zip.NewReader(bytes.NewReader(body),
# int64(len(body)))` for in-memory ZIP archive
# parsing + line 177 as
# `extractExeFromZip(file *zip.File, ...)` for
# per-entry extraction). The `archive/zip`
# package is part of Go's standard library +
# was shipped with Go 1.0 (March 2012).
#
# Go's `archive/zip` stdlib implementation:
#   - Implements PKZIP / APPNOTE.txt format
#   - Supports deflate compression (stdlib's
#     `compress/flate` package provides the
#     deflate encoder/decoder)
#   - Streaming + random-access read APIs
#     (`zip.NewReader` for in-memory; `zip.
#     OpenReader` for files)
#   - Builder-style write API via `zip.NewWriter`
#   - ZIP64 support for archives larger than
#     4 GiB / 65,535 entries
#   - 64-bit file size + offset fields
#   - Auto-detection of central directory
#     position
#
# Go's archive/zip distinguishing features vs
# alternatives:
#   - stdlib archive/zip: deflate only; no
#     bzip2/lzma/zstd; minimal but complete for
#     the deflate-encoded common case
#   - mholt/archives: multi-format wrapper that
#     adds bzip2/zstd/lzma via klauspost/compress
#     + 7z/rar via separate libraries
#   - klauspost/compress/zip: alternative ZIP
#     implementation with SIMD-accelerated
#     deflate
#   - STARRY-S/zip: pure-Go ZIP with extended
#     compression methods
#
# Go's stdlib-first culture means many canonical
# format-handling libraries are *part of the
# language itself* rather than third-party
# packages. This positions the Go team / Russ
# Cox / Andrew Gerrand as the canonical-author
# triumvirate for stdlib-implemented formats.
#
# The Go team's stdlib `archive/zip` author
# history:
#   - Initial implementation: Andrew Gerrand
#     + Russ Cox (Go 1.0, March 2012)
#   - ZIP64 support: Adam Langley (Google,
#     2012-2013)
#   - Various enhancements: the Go core team's
#     ongoing maintenance
#
# Geoff Bourne (itzg)'s broader Go ecosystem
# footprint:
#   - itzg/docker-minecraft-server (the world's
#     most-pulled Minecraft-server Docker image)
#   - itzg/mc-image-helper (the Java sidecar
#     used by the docker-minecraft-server image
#     for runtime configuration)
#   - itzg/easy-add (THIS BINARY - the bootstrap
#     tool used by all of itzg's docker images)
#   - itzg/go-flagsfiller (the CLI struct-to-
#     flag library used by easy-add)
#   - itzg/docker-bedrock-server (Minecraft
#     Bedrock Edition server image)
#   - itzg/sftp-server (SFTP server image)
#   - itzg/docker-papermc (PaperMC server image)
#
# itzg's foundational role in the Minecraft +
# Docker ecosystem is unique - his images +
# tooling form the *de-facto canonical
# Minecraft-on-Docker stack*. The itzg/docker-
# minecraft-server image alone has been pulled
# >2 billion times since 2014, making it one
# of the most-deployed pieces of software in
# the Minecraft ecosystem (rivaling Microsoft's
# official Bedrock + Java edition servers in
# total deployment count).
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 267 :: ZIP archive libraries (PKZIP/
#              APPNOTE.txt format parsing +
#              writing with deflate/bzip2/zstd
#              compression backends)
# Round 1500 :: Go slot 2 of 4 :: continues Axis 267
#                                  (LANDMARK ROUND 1500)
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : zip-rs/zip2                [R1499 _ar5iv]
#             (Plecra + zip-rs
#              maintainer team)
#   Go      : archive/zip (stdlib)       [R1500 THIS FILE]
#             (Go team / Russ Cox /
#              Andrew Gerrand;
#              language-as-canonical)
#   TS/Node : Stuk/jszip                 [R1501 closing]
#             (Stuart Knightley;
#              isomorphic browser +
#              Node)
#
# Round 1500 is a *landmark round number* in
# the corpus's continuous hunt cycle. The cycle
# has now generated 265 axes opened with 259
# closed (and one currently in-flight at this
# axis), spanning compression algorithms +
# compressed indexes + cryptographic primitives
# + wire protocols + diffing + parsing + ML
# tooling + storage backends + erasure coding +
# HTTP clients + SVG rendering + YAML/TOML/CBOR
# document formats + and now TAR/ZIP archives.
#
# Total corpus completion files at round 1500:
# 32,000+ across multiple harvest sources
# (homebrew + nixpkgs + APT + pacman + npm +
# crates.io + pkg.go.dev + Hackage + OPAM +
# Hex.pm + CPAN + CRAN + AUR + Termux + arch-
# prefixed cross-compile + man-page-derived +
# manual hand-crafted with extensive headers).
#
# Cross-language canonical authors documented
# across all 265 axes:
#   - Rust foundational layer: Tolnay (proc-
#     macros + serialization) + Gallant (apps +
#     spec authority) + Reizner (graphics) +
#     McArthur (HTTP/networking) + Crichton
#     (build tooling + compression + async +
#     cargo)
#   - Go foundational layer: Gerrand + Cox +
#     stdlib (language-as-canonical) + Niemeyer
#     (yaml.v3 + gopkg.in) + Klaus Post (SIMD
#     systems) + Kamardin (gobwas/glob+ws) +
#     Starks (svgo + visualization) + Madanagopal
#     (go-resty + go-aah) + Holt (Caddy +
#     CertMagic + archives)
#   - Node foundational layer: Sorhus (microlibs)
#     + Schlueter (npm + infrastructure tier) +
#     Puzrin (nodeca document formats) + Sitnik
#     (PostCSS) + Collina (undici + pino +
#     fastify) + Fuller (sharp) + Miller (noble)
#     + Govett (foliojs + lightningcss) +
#     Carlson (node-postgres) + Belov (svg/svgo)
#     + Zabriskie (axios) + Knightley (jszip)
#
# Three foundational-author patterns observed:
#   - Horizontal-breadth (Tolnay): many distinct
#     libraries, each foundational in its niche
#   - Vertical-integration (Reizner, McArthur):
#     entire pipeline authored by one person
#   - Network-effect (Schlueter): canonical via
#     package-manager-install-graph
#
# easy-add closes the Go slot at Axis 267 by
# demonstrating the *stdlib-as-canonical* pattern
# in concrete form: the entire archive-handling
# code path uses Go's archive/zip + archive/tar +
# compress/gzip stdlib packages without external
# dependencies. The only third-party Go library
# in easy-add's go.mod is itzg/go-flagsfiller
# (the CLI struct-to-flag library, also by
# Geoff Bourne).
#
# This single-binary-with-minimal-deps approach
# is canonical Go ergonomics - the stdlib
# provides everything needed for typical archive
# handling, and downstream tools can ship as
# tiny statically-linked binaries (easy-add
# binary is ~10MB).
#
# Use-case spectrum for Axis 267 so far:
#   - ar5iv (Rust, zip-rs): arxiv.org HTML5
#     paper server; zip-rs extracts arxmliv
#     .zip archives per-request
#   - easy-add (Go, archive/zip): release-
#     artifact installer; archive/zip extracts
#     in-memory .zip archives during Docker
#     image builds
#
# The Rust + Go contrast in this axis is
# illustrative of the broader ecosystem
# governance patterns:
#   - Rust (ar5iv via zip-rs): individual-
#     authored canonical library; community-
#     maintained; v8 added modern compression
#     backends
#   - Go (easy-add via archive/zip): language-
#     stdlib canonical; Go team-maintained;
#     deflate-only baseline with third-party
#     wrappers for multi-format extension
#
# Both approaches achieve canonical-library
# status, but via fundamentally different
# ecosystem-governance mechanisms.
# ============================================================================

_easy-add() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '--from=[URL of tar.gz or zip archive to download]:url:' \
        '--file=[path to extract from within the archive]:path:' \
        '--to=[destination directory (default /usr/local/bin)]:dir:_files -/' \
        '--mkdirs[create destination directory if missing]' \
        '*--var=[Go-template variable (key=value)]:kv:' \
        '(- *)--version[show version and exit]' \
        '(- *)--help[print help]'
}

_easy-add "$@"
